Unilever Plc

Unilever House 100 Victoria Embankment
London  EC4Y 0DY United Kingdom
Phone: +44 20 ____ ____
Fax: +44 20 ____ ____
http://www.unilever.com





545
Managers




6329
IT employees




$2.4BEST.
IT Budget




Unilever is a worldwide manufacturer of packaged consumer goods operating in Asia, Africa, North America, the Middle East, Western Europe, and Latin America. The company's products cover two categories: food and home, and personal care. Its brands include Axe, Dove,… MoreUnilever is a worldwide manufacturer of packaged consumer goods operating in Asia, Africa, North America, the Middle East, Western Europe, and Latin America. The company's products cover two categories: food and home, and personal care. Its brands include Axe, Dove, Pond's, Suave, Vaseline, Signal, Snuggle, Surf, Slim Fast, Lipton, Ben & Jerry's, Breyers, and Country Crock. Unilever maintains two headquarters locations in the Netherlands and the UK. 

Procurement Process:
The company's group procurement organization oversees both direct procurement (consisting of materials necessary for product development and manufacture) and indirect procurement (consisting of items supporting internal business operations). IT is managed within the company's indirect procurement processes. The Chief Procurement Officer is located in Singapore.
IT Priorities:
•Risk management systems within IT systems supporting all business areas are being centralized and automated.
•Gradually investing in modernizing IT infrastructure.
•Developing new digital marketing strategies is an important part of the company's long term business strategy.

2013 and Previously:

Unilever is a worldwide… MoreIT Priorities:
•Risk management systems within IT systems supporting all business areas are being centralized and automated.
•Gradually investing in modernizing IT infrastructure.
•Developing new digital marketing strategies is an important part of the company's long term business strategy.

2013 and Previously:

Unilever is a worldwide manufacturer of packaged consumer goods operating in Asia, Africa, North America, the Middle East, Western Europe, and Latin America. The company's products cover two categories: food and home, and personal care. Its brands include Axe, Dove, Pond's, Suave, Vaseline, Signal, Snuggle, Surf, Slim Fast, Lipton, Ben & Jerry's, Breyers, and Country Crock. Unilever is part of the Unilever Group owned by the Netherlands-based Unilever N.V. and UK-based Unilever PLC.

The Global CIO, who is located at the company's headquarters in London, leads the IT department at Unilever. Another key figure in the department is the Chief Technology Officer, whose focus is on IT architecture, as well as global information security.

These top executives rely on vice presidents whose duties range from company-wide initiatives dealing with SAP to the provision of IT services. For example, there is an executive in charge of information management who is dedicated to ensuring that the local and divisional level business leaders get financial reports with the level of aggregation appropriate to their level of responsibility. Other executives with a regional focus manage IT for Europe, regional application integration, and IT for the AMETCEE region.

Two of the VPs and a director handle the provision of IT services on a regional basis. The VP of Enterprise Computing Services is concerned with the data center initiatives in Europe. The VP of Global IT Services manages service desk operations, telecommunications, and networks. The Director of Global IT Innovation handles other aspects of IT services and business partnering, including agreements for application services.

The company relies on key outsourcing partners in some areas. To manage these relationships, the Director of Global Services is involved with service delivery. Preparing and monitoring the contracts involves the Director of Global IT Finance, whose duties include the financial aspects involved in preparing the outsourcing agreement, but also in the benchmarking and performance monitoring necessary once the contracts are in place.

Other IT directors handle financial applications and strategic architecture. There are also managers working on security architecture and SAP services. There is also a business application architect working with the CTO and an IT business partner for R&D.

The company uses SAP as its primary enterprise resource planning (ERP) application, and prefers off the shelf solutions to custom application development. IT works closely with its IT service providers. HP was brought in to manage data center operations in the Americas, Asia, Africa, Turkey, and the Middle East. 

Unilever also has a contract with BT for the innovation and management of its supply chain. The company works with Accenture to implement a unified IT platform for Europe and relies on products and services from IBM and Oracle.

In order to keep costs low, the company recently implemented a Microsoft private cloud infrastructure in which it uses Windows server 2008 R2 and Windows server 2012 and virtualizes those servers using Hyper-V technology.

Estimates of the company's total IT workforce near 4,000, with as many as 3,000 of its staff members involved with IT professionals stationed in Europe.

Unilever US is maintained as a separate profile.





